														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2831323">
									

<ul>
<li><strong>Edgy content</strong>
<ul>
<li>Rape, nazis, pedophilia, homophobia, genocide&#8230; and so on. As far as shocking your audience goes, these are trite, and careless handling of these topics does actually cause real distress (as opposed to the voyeuristic kind that horror is supposed to provide).</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Scope mismatch</strong>
<ul>
<li>A good article will comfortably cover the topic at hand and is engaging every step of the way. Sometimes, people get an idea for an anomaly, explain the whole thing, and post it without realizing they just spent six paragraphs describing a toaster that freezes toast. Or maybe they spend one paragraph describing kilometer-wide ghoul-filled underground facility and decide that's fine. An SCP should be the same size as its idea.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>They don't care about the idea</strong>
<ul>
<li>Articles the author didn't care about are obvious &#8212; hastily written, derivative, and lifeless. There's no trick you can use to make it seem like you care about more than having an article to your name, except <em>actually caring</em> about the article for its own sake. Writing SCPs is <em>easy</em> for me, and I don't even <em>attempt</em> to write until an idea grabs me and demands to be written.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>I'll add more if I think of anything.</p>

