					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/procyonlotor" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(778357); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=778357&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204978" alt="ProcyonLotor" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=778357)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/procyonlotor" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(778357); return false;" >ProcyonLotor</a></span> <span class="odate time_1495645298 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 May 2017 17:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2831328">
									

<ul>
<li><strong>Discovery before Actual Description:</strong> One of the worst structural remnants of early Series I. In (almost) every case, what it is and what it does is more important than where it was found, and those should thusly lead the Description section.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Lack of Proofing:</strong> This would seem like an obvious one, right? Make sure you've got your capitalization sorted, your its/it's sorted, and your spelling and phrasing correct before posting. We all fuck up, and a stray error or two will rarely be enough to earn my downvote, but the grammar and spelling should be <em>substantially</em> correct before it is posted.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Wooden Dialogue:</strong> The absolute quickest way to kill my suspension of disbelief. Nothing will earn my downvote more swiftly than obviously fake dialogue. Best fiction writing advice I've ever received: read your dialogue aloud, and see if it sounds like an actual conversation. If it doesn't, adjust it until it does.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Too Much Content for the Idea:</strong> A lot of people critique drafts as &quot;too short&quot; nowadays. And while this is obviously often a correct criticism, it has led to the rise of the opposite problem: reams and reams of texts for ideas that aren't interesting enough to support it. Some ideas can only be sufficiently explored in five or six paragraphs and a few addendums; others are perfectly fine at three paragraphs. Being boring because it's overexplored can be just as problematic as being boring because it's underdeveloped.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Shoe-horned GOIs:</strong> The vast majority of successful works with GOIs involved began with the intention of specifically including that GOI. And while occasionally good GOI connections will develop in the natural creation of a draft, &quot;what if I made this bastard a Little Mister&quot; rarely works.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Saturated Concepts:</strong> I don't necessarily mean cliches, but there's a lot of stuff where we probably have enough articles for the broad idea. These range from very large concepts with a significant number of articles, like parasites, to (relatively) niche concepts with a smaller number of articles, like nuclear weapons or retro video games.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Randomly Glorifying Specific Characters:</strong> This is usually, but not always, self-inserts. The Foundation's a competent organization, they're probably not going to have one person doing all the research and granting all the authorization for a skip.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Too Much, or Not Enough, Mystery:</strong> By far the hardest thing to master here, and not necessarily applicable to every article. Many articles live and die on the questions they raise. But a balance must be struck: if you overexplain everything, often in a note in the end, you kill a lot of the fascination. But if you underexplain (or, worse, overredact), your readers won't care. Questioning and curiosity is a form of reader engagement- and good reader engagement is an almost certain guarantee of a successful article.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Lack of Proper Security:</strong> Unless it's well done and explained (<a href="/scp-2310">SCP-2310</a> is an excellent example of this), Foundation employees should not be catching the idiot ball. I see a specific variant of this very often in coldposts (and, admittedly, a lot of older articles); a researcher goes in to interview a horrifically dangerous anomaly that has been in no way secured, researcher angers anomaly, anomaly says something spooky and predictably kills researcher. Researchers are not an infinite resource. If the anomaly would obviously kill anyone who goes in to talk to them, they're not going to send in anyone to talk to them, but would instead find some other way. Same with D-Class. While the Foundation's treatment and use of D-Class is well beyond the scope of this thread, in any construction it's unreasonable for them to just be thrown away pointlessly.</li>
</ul>

							</div>

								
