															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scorpion451" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1918720); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1918720&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204978" alt="Scorpion451" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1918720)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scorpion451" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1918720); return false;" >Scorpion451</a></span> <span class="odate time_1495646625 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 May 2017 17:23</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2831340">
									

<p>Getting the science wrong, especially basic science.<br />
Yes, anomalies are anomalous.<br />
No, that is not a free pass to handwave everything.<br />
Botching the scientific analysis of an SCP can be equally bad.<br />
Examples:</p>
<ul>
<li>A substance being unidentifiable is <em>itself</em> an anomaly. Even if you can't damage something, there are other ways to analyze it's makeup, like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X-ray_Crystallography" onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;">X-ray Crystallography</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectroscopy" onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;">Spectroscopy</a>.</li>
<li>Pure energy is not a thing. This is because energy only has meaning in relation to matter. It can be stored in matter<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-956753-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-956753-1')">1</a></sup>; it can do things <em>to</em> matter; it can be stored in the relative locations of matter<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-956753-2" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-956753-2')">2</a></sup>Photons are the closest thing to &quot;beams of pure energy&quot;, and you'll note that they are typically described as particles. This is because we use a different name for energy that isn't attached to matter somehow: matter. Yes, this is complicated and confusing. No, you can't ignore it.</li>
<li>Biology is not magic, and nature is the best sci fi horror writer. There are actual organisms that shapeshift, glow in the dark, turn invisible, assimilate parts of other organisms, thrive in nuclear reactor cores, attack and eat anything that comes into biting range, reproduce by exploding, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone_snail" onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;">produce complex cocktails of toxins that hack the nervous system to work almost instantaneously, which they use to coat harpoons fired from an organic tank turret</a>. And don't even get me started on (mind-controlling) parasites. Real organisms are both your best source of inspiration and greatest competition when it comes to designing monsters.</li>
<li>Messing with the laws of the universe has a name: Abstract Mathematics. A lot of mathematicians spend their entire careers studying things like <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory">systems where 2+2=5</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topology">warped topological spaces that are bigger on the inside</a>, the properties of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimension">hyperdimensional objects and spaces</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_theory">math without the concept of numbers</a>. If you want to get esoteric, be prepared: here there be eldritch math-dragons you must tame with research, and then find a way to explain to your readers in an interesting way.</li>
</ul>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-956753-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-956753-1')">1</a>. in forms like kinetic energy/heat/acoustic vibration (same thing in different shapes and scales, really), mechanical energy(think compressed springs), and chemical &amp; electrical energy (electrons being held somewhere or moving somewhere else)</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-956753-2"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-956753-2')">2</a>. static electricity(location of free electrons), potential kinetic energy, etc</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
