															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/moist-spaghetti" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1387731); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1387731&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204978" alt="Moist Spaghetti" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1387731)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/moist-spaghetti" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1387731); return false;" >Moist Spaghetti</a></span> <span class="odate time_1495648032 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 May 2017 17:47</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2831354">
									

<p>Major problems I see a lot</p>
<ul>
<li>Using &quot;It's&quot; as possessive. For example, lets write &quot;SCP-XXXX has lost its mind&quot;. Do you use &quot;its&quot; or &quot;it's&quot;? Whenever you write &quot;it's&quot;, try replacing it with &quot;it is&quot; and see if it still makes sense. From our previous sentence, &quot;SCP-XXXX has lost it is mind&quot;. Does that many any sense?</li>
<li>Things that kill you with no backstory. I tried re-writing an SCP once. Turned out terrible. The idea was meh, but there was no backstory. That's a lot of articles downfall. Lots of scips are just things that kill you, <strong>but</strong> most of them have a really interesting backstory.</li>
<li>Katanas. Seriously, calm down with katanas. They're not the ultimate sword, they're just okay.</li>
<li>Interview logs. In articles that are already kind of bad, the interview logs stand out as the worst. Usually, the interviewer asks a vague question, the scip answers with &quot;you wouldn't understand&quot; or &quot;he is coming&quot; or something edgy, then they kill the researcher and there's a containment breach with [ERROR: VALUE TOO LARGE] casualties.</li>
<li>Slapping Keter/Euclid on everything. Not many new people start out with a simple, safe object. A lot of times you'll get something like a stick of gum that kills you if you eat it, and it's also keter cause it'll kill you.</li>
<li>Talking in the second person. This is kinda self explanatory. The article shouldn't be directed towards a specific audience (i.e. don't write to the readers, write in a general tone)</li>
<li>Containment procedures. The Foundation is a prison, not a spa. I've seen a few articles where there were people with little anomalous properties, but they were given access to Safe/Euclid SCPs and could roam the facility. On the other hand, some things are over-secured. You don't need 5 armed guards and constant surveillance for a safe level object. Also, sometimes containment procedures aren't explained in the writing. I remember an article where the scip could only be lit by ultraviolet lights, but there wasn't an explanation why.</li>
<li>Guns. Guns are more complicated then people know. People get a lot of things wrong with guns, and it really, really bugs me.</li>
<li>Grammar. Generally, the main things I see with grammar is lack of/too much spacing, run on sentences, and incorrect/no capitalization.</li>
<li>Images. A lot of articles with image problems either have two things going on. Either the image i just stretching across the screen with no explanation text, or the explanation text is un-clinical (e.g. &quot;Here is a photo of SCP-XXXX in its active state&quot; versus &quot;SCP-XXXX in its active state&quot;)</li>
<li>Testing logs. If your testing logs don't add anything to the article, or are just boring, then I suggest either revising them or scrapping em.</li>
<li>Plagiarism. There's a lot of copies of slenderman and 106 that I've seen, including a couple that are combinations of both. Be original.</li>
<li>Descriptions. The main problem I've seen the most with descriptions is how they're organized. Usually, the description goes: What it is, what it looks like (or swap with what it does), what it does, and then special notes like recovery information.</li>
</ul>

							</div>

